lative trail-blazer, enacting progressive legislation well before England and Wales. And Scotland voted overwhelmingly to remain in the European Union, putting it at odds with much of the rest of the United Kingdom on the most important political decision this century. The country has transformed from the socially and politically conservative climate of the post-war period to a nation contemplating, for the second time, a move to independence – for all the uncertainty and turmoil that would bring. At a time when the country’s future has topped the agenda in Britain and abroad, this book unpicks the complex weave of Scottish politics, society and culture, providing an essential insight into Scotland’s present – and its future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHome rulezScotland. 4aPolitical Studies 2020. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  aDiaspora.  aElites.  aEthnicity.  aGender.  aHeritage.  aIdentity.  aPolicy.  aPolitics.  aScotland.  aSociology.1 aLeith, Murray Stewart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcTavish, Duncan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSim, Duncan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSim, Duncan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTorrance, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612779240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526127792423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526127792/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles